SIMPLE: mechanism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mechanism
<hw>Mech"an*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>m⟦eacute⟧canisme</ets>, L. <ets>mechanisma</ets>. See
<er>Mechanic</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The arrangement or relation
of the parts of a machine; the parts of a machine, taken collectively;
the arrangement or relation of the parts of anything as adapted to
produce an effect; <as>as, the <ex>mechanism</ex> of a watch; the
<ex>mechanism</ex> of a sewing machine; the <ex>mechanism</ex> of a seed
pod.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The series of causal relations that operate to
produce an effect in any system; <as>as, the <ex>mechanism</ex> of a
chemical reaction</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Mechanical operation or action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He acknowledges nothing besides matter and motion; so that all
must be performed either by <qex>mechanism</qex> or accident.</q>
<rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Kinematics)</fld> <def>An ideal machine; a
combination of movable bodies constituting a machine, but considered
only with regard to relative movements.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mechanism of action</ent>⟦br⟧
